<quiz>
    <question>
        <prompt>What happens to the unemployment rate when discouraged workers re-enter the labor force during recovery?</prompt>
        <options>
            <option letter="a">Unemployment rate decreases</option>
            <option letter="b">Unemployment rate increases initially</option>
            <option letter="c">Unemployment rate stays constant</option>
            <option letter="d">Only affects employment rate</option>
        </options>
        <answer>b</answer>
        <explanation>When discouraged workers re-enter the labor force, the unemployment rate initially increases because they are counted as unemployed while searching for work, even though this may indicate improving economic conditions.</explanation>
    </question>

    <question>
        <prompt>How does a decrease in aggregate supply affect the relationship between inflation and unemployment?</prompt>
        <options>
            <option letter="a">Creates lower inflation and lower unemployment</option>
            <option letter="b">Creates higher inflation and higher unemployment</option>
            <option letter="c">Creates higher inflation and lower unemployment</option>
            <option letter="d">Has no effect on inflation or unemployment</option>
        </options>
        <answer>b</answer>
        <explanation>A decrease in aggregate supply creates stagflation, with both higher inflation (due to higher costs) and higher unemployment (due to reduced output), shifting the Phillips Curve right.</explanation>
    </question>

    <question>
        <prompt>What effect does an increase in the required reserve ratio have on the money multiplier?</prompt>
        <options>
            <option letter="a">Increases the money multiplier</option>
            <option letter="b">Decreases the money multiplier</option>
            <option letter="c">Has no effect on the money multiplier</option>
            <option letter="d">Makes the money multiplier negative</option>
        </options>
        <answer>b</answer>
        <explanation>An increase in the required reserve ratio decreases the money multiplier because banks must hold more reserves for each dollar of deposits, reducing their ability to create money through lending.</explanation>
    </question>

    <question>
        <prompt>How does an increase in income inequality affect aggregate consumption spending?</prompt>
        <options>
            <option letter="a">Always increases aggregate consumption</option>
            <option letter="b">Tends to decrease aggregate consumption</option>
            <option letter="c">Has no effect on aggregate consumption</option>
            <option letter="d">Only affects investment spending</option>
        </options>
        <answer>b</answer>
        <explanation>Increased income inequality tends to decrease aggregate consumption because higher-income households have a lower marginal propensity to consume than lower-income households.</explanation>
    </question>
</quiz>
